    <item>
      <title>Trump Dismisses Concerns About New Tariffs</title>
      <author>AllSides Staff</author>
      <link>https://www.allsides.com/story/economy-and-jobs-trump-dismisses-concerns-about-new-tariffs</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.allsides.com/story/economy-and-jobs-trump-dismisses-concerns-about-new-tariffs</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 16 Oct 2024 14:08:17 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="story-id-page-description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Former President Donald Trump is dismissing concerns that new tariffs would&amp;nbsp;threaten jobs, lead to a trade war with China, and force American consumers to pay more for certain goods.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Details&lt;/strong&gt;: In an &lt;a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HlWT6nYZ4OU"&gt;interview&lt;/a&gt; Tuesday with Bloomberg editor-in-chief&amp;nbsp;John Micklethwait at the Economic Club of Chicago, Trump defended his plans to impose a universal tariff on imports. Micklethwait noted that some critics believe Trump's tariff proposals would result in a national sales tax, while Trump believes higher tariffs would encourage foreign companies to build their factories in the United States. Vice President Kamala Harris has "&lt;a href="https://www.allsides.com/news/2024-10-15-1215/politics-bloomberg-editor-harris-declined-interview-economy"&gt;so far declined&lt;/a&gt;"&amp;nbsp;an interview with Bloomberg News and the Economic Club of Chicago.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Quotes&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;“That is going to have a serious effect on the overall economy,” Micklethwait said. Trump responded,&amp;nbsp;“It’s going to have a massive effect — positive effect. It’s going to be a positive effect... It must be hard for you to spend 25 years talking about tariffs as being negative and then have somebody explain to you that you’re totally wrong.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For Context: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tariff"&gt;Tariffs&lt;/a&gt; were imposed by Congress in 1789, and trade policy has been &lt;a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/taxnotes/2024/07/31/a-history-of-tariffs-from-hamilton-to-trump/"&gt;controversial ever since that time&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;How the Media Covered it&lt;/strong&gt;: The &lt;a href="https://www.allsides.com/news-source/washington-times-bias"&gt;Washington Times&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.allsides.com/news-source/washington-times-bias"&gt; (Lean Right bias)&lt;/a&gt; noted that the Republican&amp;nbsp;Party has traditionally held to a free-trade policy but that Trump has adopted a more populist approach that appeals to many&amp;nbsp;blue-collar Americans. &lt;a href="https://www.allsides.com/news-source/cnn-media-bias"&gt;CNN&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.allsides.com/news-source/cnn-media-bias"&gt; (Lean Left bias)&lt;/a&gt; noted that President Joe Biden and Vice President Kamala Harris kept Trump's tariffs on Chinese goods in place, and noted&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w25638"&gt;studies&lt;/a&gt; suggesting American consumers have borne most of the cost of these tariffs.&lt;/p&gt;  &lt;/div&gt;</description>
